Analyzing Housing Features to Find the Best Selling Price¶

A Data Science Project using Predictive Models¶

by Shawn Lee¶

Link to GitHub repo

Link to original dataset

The dataset train.csv contains 79 different feature columns describing different aspects of houses sold in Ames, Iowa. The goal is to predict the target variable, SalePrice which is the actual selling price of the home. The goal of this prediction is to provide homeowners a reasonable, data-driven benchmark on how they might price their homes before going to market.

size_without_holdout = int(len(df)*(1 - holdout_proportion))
df_holdout = df.iloc[size_without_holdout:,:]
df_train = df.iloc[:size_without_holdout,:]

target = df_train['SalePrice']
target_holdout = df_holdout['SalePrice']

features = df_train.iloc[:, 1:-2].copy() # drops id column, target column, and 'SaleCondition' which is unobservable until the sale is actually made
features_holdout = df_holdout.iloc[:,1:-1].copy()

1. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

1.1 Visualizing the feature distributions¶

Notes:

  • Some continuous variables are heavily weighted at 0. A binary variable can be created to indicate zero or non-zero to smooth out the information in the data. This may improve the generalizability of the models. It should be noted that this increases the risk of high multicolinearity, which will be addressed in the predictive models used.
  • Some numeric variables are discrete counts of a home feature, such as FullBath, BedroomAbvGr, Fireplaces, etc. These can be converted to categorical variables before training the data. Rating data such as OverallQual, OverallCond will be treated similarly.
  • YearRemodAdd is heavily weighted at 1950. This might suggest that missing values were set to 1950 as a default.

1.2 Describing the data with some key statistics¶

In [ ]:
def eda_summary(df):
    numeric = features.select_dtypes(include=['float', 'int64']).columns
    return pd.DataFrame({
        'Mean': df[numeric].mean().round(2),
        'Std': df[numeric].std().round(2),
        'Median': df[numeric].median(),
        'Missing Values': df[numeric].isna().sum(),
        'Zero Values': (df[numeric] == 0).sum(),
        'Proportion Zero Values': ((df[numeric] == 0).sum() / len(df)).round(2),
        'Unique Values': df[numeric].nunique()
    })

features_summary = eda_summary(features)

Notes:

  • LotFrontage missing values are likely cases where the house does not have any measurable frontage as part of the lot. The same can be said for MasVnrArea. These will be converted to 0 for simplicity in the pre-processing stage.
  • GarageYrBlt missing values are likely cases where the house does not have a garage. This is a bit tricky since setting the year to 0 would not be as meaningful. Instead, the data can be imputed by replacing the mising values wih the median of GarageYrBlt. Median is used because the skew in the distribution of data suggests it is a better measure of central tendency.

2.2 Categorizing features according to notes in section 1.1¶

In [ ]:
# Initialize lists for classification
numeric = features.select_dtypes(include=['float', 'int64']).columns.tolist()
create_binary = []
categorical = []
datetime = []

# Iterate through the summary DataFrame to classify columns
for column in features_summary.index: 
    if features_summary.loc[column, 'Proportion Zero Values'] >= 0.5:  # 0.5 is arbitrary; if more than half the values of a feature are 0, a binary variable will be created to represent zero or non-zero
        create_binary.append(column)
    elif features_summary.loc[column, 'Unique Values'] <= 15: # 15 is based on the number of classes in 'MSSubClass'; if a feature has 15 or less classes, it should be considered a categorical variable
        categorical.append(column)
    if 'Year' in column or 'Yr' in column: 
        datetime.append(column)

# Adjust lists to avoid duplicate categorizing
categorical = [col for col in categorical if col not in datetime]
continuous = [col for col in numeric if col not in categorical and col not in datetime]

# Print out the classified lists
print("Numeric (Continuous):", continuous)
print("Create Binary:", create_binary)
print("Categorical:", categorical)
print("Datetime:", datetime)

2.5 Adjusting skewness on remaining continuous variables¶

Some predictive models may perform better when the data is not skewed. Reducing skewness can be done through Box-Cox transformations. It should be considered that such transformations should only be applied to meaningfully skewed data (skew > 1).

In [ ]:
# observe the skew of all continuous variables

In [ ]:
# Apply Box-Cox transformations on data with skew > 1
excluded_columns = []
successful_transforms = []

for column in continuous:
    try:
        if abs(skewness[column]) > 1:
            min_value = features[column].min()            # Adjust data by adding a constant if any values are non-positive
            shift = 0
            if min_value <= 0:
                shift = abs(min_value) + 1
            features[column], fitted_lambda = boxcox(features[column] + shift)
            successful_transforms.append(column)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Skipping {column} due to error: {e}")
        excluded_columns.append(column)
        
# Display the new skewness values for the transformed columns
new_skewness = features[successful_transforms].skew()
print(new_skewness)

# Plot the distributions of the transformed columns
features[successful_transforms].hist(bins=20, figsize=(10, 4))

3.1 Looking for high correlations in features¶

In [ ]:

It should be noted that when picking which variable to remove from a high-correlation pair, the choice of which variable has a salient effect on the information loss. To minimize this, both variables in the high-correlation pair should have its average correlation with all other variables evaluated. The variable with the higher average correlation with all other variables is the one that will be removed. The function below returns a list of removed varaibles until no pair exceeds the correlation threshold specified.

Also worth noting is that because correlation is not a scaled measure, we do not expect to find correlations between the continuous variables and the datetime variables. We cannot apply standard scaling to the datetime variables because the underlying distribution is expected to be non-normal and, in general, time-series data should be handled as a special case. This exercise is specifically expected to tease out which datetime variables have a high correlation with other datetime variables.

In [ ]:
def remove_predictors(data, threshold):    
    data_reduced=data.copy()
    predictors_to_remove = []
    while True:
        # Calculate the correlation matrix of the predictors
        corr_mat = data_reduced.corr()
        # Get the absolute pairwise correlations
        corr_mat = np.abs(corr_mat)
        np.fill_diagonal(corr_mat.values, 0)
        corr_mat=corr_mat.fillna(0)
        
        if corr_mat.max().max()<threshold:
            break
        
        # Determine the two predictors associated with the largest absolute pairwise correlation
        max_corr = np.unravel_index(np.argmax(corr_mat), corr_mat.shape)
        predictor_A = max_corr[0]
        predictor_B = max_corr[1]
        
        # Determine the average absolute correlation between A and the other variables
        avg_corr_A = np.mean(corr_mat.iloc[predictor_A, :])
        avg_corr_B = np.mean(corr_mat.iloc[predictor_B, :])
        
        # If A has a larger average correlation, remove it; otherwise, remove predictor B
        if avg_corr_A > avg_corr_B:
            remove_predictor = predictor_A
            retained_predictor = predictor_B
            predictors_to_remove.append(data_reduced.columns.tolist()[remove_predictor])
        else:
            remove_predictor = predictor_B
            retained_predictor = predictor_A
            predictors_to_remove.append(data_reduced.columns.tolist()[remove_predictor])
        
        # Remove the predictor
        print(f'Remove: {data_reduced.columns.tolist()[remove_predictor]} and Retain: {data_reduced.columns.tolist()[retained_predictor]}')

        del data_reduced[data_reduced.columns.tolist()[remove_predictor]]

    return predictors_to_remove

columns_to_remove = remove_predictors(features_scaled[corr_columns], 0.7)

4. Model Building¶

Before we begin making predictions, we should look at the target variable we are trying to predict.

In [ ]:
plt.hist(target)
plt.title('Histogram of SalePrice')
plt.xlabel('USD')
plt.ylabel('Observations')
plt.show()

The sale prices of houses are clearly skewed to the right. This is problematic for us because we will be tuning our models using k-folds cross validation, and a skewed dataset may introduce misrepresentative samples to train our model on. To address this, we can once again treat for skewness, this time by taking the log(SalePrice).

In [ ]:
log_target = np.log(target)

plt.xlabel('USD')

This looks better.

Before model fitting, there is one final note to be considered. Traditionally, this may be considered a time-series problem as temporal data have characteristics that impact the choice of models for analysis. Because the goal is not specifically about forecasting future data, datetime features will be treated as a categorical feature for simplicity. It is also worth noting that models such as XGBoost would treat datetime features similarly, even in forecasting applications.

# Initialize the ElasticNet model
elastic_net_model = ElasticNet(max_iter=10000)

# Define the grid of hyperparameters to search
param_grid = {
    'alpha': [0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0],  # Regularization strength
    'l1_ratio': np.arange(0.0, 1.2, 0.2)  # The ElasticNet mixing parameter, with 0 <= l1_ratio <= 1
}

# Set up the GridSearchCV object with negative mean squared error as the scoring method
grid_search_en = GridSearchCV(estimator=elastic_net_model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=n_folds, 
                              scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the GridSearchCV object to the scaled features and log-target
grid_search_en.fit(features_scaled, log_target)

# Get the best parameters and negative MSE score
best_params_en = grid_search_en.best_params_
best_score_en = -grid_search_en.best_score_  # Convert to positive MSE

# Convert the best MSE score to RMSE
best_score_rmse_en = np.sqrt(best_score_en)

print(f'Best parameters found for Elastic Net: {best_params_en}')
print(f'Best CV Score (Root Mean Squared Error for Elastic Net with GridSearch): {best_score_rmse_en:,.4f}')

# The best estimator can be used for predictions or further analysis
best_en_model = grid_search_en.best_estimator_

6. Results interpretation¶

  • As expected, Random Forest performed a bit better compared to the Decision Tree as the ensemble approach of the former model introduces more nuance in its prediction.
  • ElasticNet had notable performance on the training set, but saw a significant loss in performance on the holdout set. This suggests substantial overfitting issues.
  • SVM did well on the training set, but saw some decline in the holdout set. The magnitude of performance loss is more in line with expectations when testing on unseen data and does not immediately suggest overfitting.
  • Consistent with current trends in the field of Data Science and Machine Learning, XGBoost is still the best in class for performing prediction tasks.

While it was evident that there were better performing models for this prediction task, it should be noted that the original linear regression model in section 4.1 was not even considered in the overall model selection. It is possible that this could have been improved by passing in variables from Principal Component Analaysis (PCA) or Partial Least Squares (PLS) to improve its performance, but these were ultimately not considered in the interest of maintaining some interpretability.

7. Conclusion¶

The range of tools available to make predictions are richer and more versatile than ever. It is up to the user to masterfully temper and apply these tools appropriately. In this project alone, several pitfalls to predictive analysis were already revealed:

  • At the very beginning of the notebook, it was necessary to omit the 'SaleCondition' column because this is information that would only be available concurrent to the target variable being predicted. To include this in the model would allow it to "see into the future", given our research goal of predicting a reasonable selling price for a house.
  • There is no blanket approach to imputing missing values in the dataset. In this sample, it was necessary to coalesce some variables to zero, while for another variable, getting the median was deemed more appropriate.
  • Not all numerical variables should be treated equally. Part of our feature engineering involved decisions to treat continuous variables as binary and categorical.
  • Datetime variables can be tricky to handle, but depending on the model and research question, assumptions can be made to simplify this complexity.
  • Feature engineering can sometimes require a mix of domain knowledge an computational knowledge. Due to the nature of datetime variables, it was clearly not appropriate to apply standard scaling.
  • For production and execution, it would be beneficial to incorporate Python's object-oriented programing. This would result in cleaner, more readable code, especially when handling the pre-processing and transformations of the holdout dataset.
  • As much as possible, it is important to retain some portion of the dataset as the holdout and final test. It was evident that even powerful models need to be fine-tuned so as not to overfit on training data.
  • Even with such strong predictive tools, the limitation persists that these models are not able to provide meaningful estimates of the $\beta$'s of how a change in one feature may affect the sale price of a house.
